e:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ommittee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our Policing Plan priorities for 2013-14 are Counter-Terrorism, Economic Crime, Public Order, Crime Reduction, Road Safety and Antisocial Behaviour. The priorities are underpinned by a small number of performance measures or targets. Delivery of these targ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ets </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> monitored and scrutinised by the Force’s Performance Management Group </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(which is attended by Police Authority </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">staff</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the Head of the Community Safety Team</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Corporation’s Performance Management Team</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Chairman of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Performance &amp; Res</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ources Management </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(Police) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sub-Committee</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whilst the Police Committee sets a target to reduce crime, this does not stipulate a numerical or percentage reduction. In addition, the Committee is working with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">City of London Police</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to consider how new cri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">me outcomes can support policing priorities next year. Currently, no specific targets have been set on detection rates.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  This approach reduces the potential impact on our police recording crime practices.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Impact on Police Crime Recording Practices</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">impact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of using performance targets </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on current police crime practices is minimal – as there are adequate checks </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> balances in place to ensure that police crime recording practices are robust.  Assurances are provided by the checks (set out below). In add</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ition, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ny in-year adjustments to the crime </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">performance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">statistics are challenged by the Corporation and the Police Committee Members – particularly with regard to satisfaction statistics, the violent crime </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> acquisitive crime statistics. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The Force’s AC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PO team also routinely seek assurance through the commissioning of independent audits.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Force has embarked on a cultural change programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“City Futures” – which aims to make the City of London Police </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“a worldwide centre of excellence for our policin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g services”. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Part of the programme of change is a focus on improving service delivery through the setting of robust </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">service </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">outcomes – that will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">improve service performance. The new arrangements will include a further strengthening of the Force’s police r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ecording practices to ensure that they are robust</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transparent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How do you assure yourself that the recorded crime figures for your area are correct? To what extent can you trust the crime statistics for your area? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As a Police </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthority, there are a n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">umber of ways where we are assured about the reliability of our crime statistics.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The following checks </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(provide the Police Authority with a level of assurance that the crime statistics are reliable)</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Independent Audit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> commissioned by the Force</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Force commissioned an independent audit of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">crime data in June 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> carried out by a team who had previously worked for HMIC on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ata </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Q</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uality inspections.  The outcome of this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">review</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">received</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Performance and Resource Management S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ub-committee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (P &amp; RM Sub-committee) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in September 2013 </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">concluded that: </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘There is clear evidence that ethical crime and incident data is of utmost importance within the City of London. ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he City of London police maintains an impressively h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">igh standard of capturing reports of crime, thus ensuring such crimes are correctly classified. The force Crime and Incident Registrar remains a strong and powerful advocate for ethical decision making.’ </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Independent Auditors also commented favourably </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Force’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">governance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> arrangements -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which ensured that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the quality of incident and crime recording remained an area of strategic focus.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">HMIC Review of Crime </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Incident Reports</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The HMIC conduct</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a regular review of Crime and Incident reports to ensure the correct and ethical reporting of both, and that incidents are correctly classified as crimes when necessary. The last COLP report was published in January 2012, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Crimes in the City o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">f London are generally recorded accurately and in accordance with National Crime Recording Standards (NCRS).” </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The City of London Police efficiently recorded and classified reports of crimes”. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The report concluded</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">senior officers in the force were clear</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ly committed to maintaining high standards of crime recording, and this was well supported by police committee. The force conducts comprehensive crime and incident audit programmes, the results of which are presented at regular crime performance meetings. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This means the force can have confidence in the crime figures it produces</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.”</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Police Routine Checks</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Force regularly reviews </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">crime recording standards to supplement the HMIC inspection work. In addition, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Force’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> integrity dashboard reported to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Police Committee includes a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> update on the monthly dip sampling of crime reports</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ensure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> standards are maintained.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Future </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">City </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Corporation of London </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Internal Audit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Checks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Corporation is currently considering introducing a further independent check of Crime Statistics through the Corporation’s Internal Audit Service.  The plan is to build it into their annual Police audit programme.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">The P &amp; RM Sub-committee is a sub-committee of our Police Committee and its remit is to ensure the Force is efficient, effective and delivering value for money.</span></p></body></html>